---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Who do I book first — the window installer or the painter?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Window installer first, painter second. Replacing a window almost always damages the surrounding paint line — the old architraves get pried, the reveal gets touched up with sealant, and the new frame's flanges sit slightly differently. The painter then comes in, makes good the damaged sections and rolls a fresh coat. Doing it the other way around (paint first, then windows) means paying the painter to come back. The exception is full-house repaint where the windows are already locked in — then you can scaffold once and both trades work in parallel."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will replacing my Berwick windows void anything on my garage door?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Not the garage door itself, but it can affect the BAL (Bushfire Attack Level) and energy rating of the whole house if your Berwick property sits in a bushfire-prone area (parts of Berwick-Beaconsfield foothills are BAL-12.5 or BAL-19). New windows have to match or exceed the BAL rating of the existing envelope. The garage door, side glazing and any roller-door glass need to be on the same standard — AS 3959 requires consistency. If you're replacing windows alongside a new sectional or panel-lift garage door, share the BAL certificate between trades so both products match."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I retrofit double glazing without replacing the whole window?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "On many Berwick aluminium frames, yes — IGU (insulated glazing unit) retrofit swaps just the glass and seals while keeping the existing frame. Cost is 40–60% of a full window replacement and the energy performance lift is similar (U-value drops from ~5.5 down to ~2.7). The catch: older single-glazed frames weren't designed for the extra weight of an IGU, so the frame, sash and hinges have to be inspected first. Timber frames usually retrofit well; thin aluminium frames sometimes don't. We assess and tell you honestly which way is better value."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need a building permit to replace windows in City of Casey?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Like-for-like replacement (same size, same opening type) is usually permit-exempt under Schedule 3 of the Building Regulations. Changing the opening size, adding a new window, or converting a sliding door to French doors triggers a building permit through a private surveyor and lodgement with City of Casey. Heritage overlays (parts of Berwick Village) add a planning permit requirement on top — you can't change window style or frame colour without council approval. We check the overlay before quoting and lodge the permit if needed."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Local Trades in City of Casey: Window Replacement & the Trades it Works With | Berwick Window Replacement"
  description="How window and sliding door replacement sits alongside garage doors, painters and double glazing in Berwick and the City of Casey — BAL ratings, AS 2047 install standards, heritage overlay considerations and council references."
  canonical="https://berwickwindowreplacement.com.au/local-trades/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Local trades &amp; the building envelope</span>
      <h1>The <span class="accent">Casey trades</span> that work alongside a window replacement.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Replacing windows touches more trades than most owners expect &mdash;
        the painter has to make good the reveals, the garage door has to share
        the same BAL rating, and a glazing upgrade only delivers its full
        energy lift when the rest of the envelope is sealed too. Here&rsquo;s
        how the trades line up in Berwick and the City of Casey.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Free window quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">The envelope team</span>
      <h2>Trades on a typical Berwick window replacement.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width:65rem;">
        <p>
          A window replacement looks self-contained until you start
          pulling the old frame out. Suddenly the architrave needs
          patching, the reveal needs sealing, the paint line is broken,
          and if you&rsquo;re upgrading to double glazing the whole
          envelope story comes into play. Here are the trades we
          coordinate with most often on Casey jobs.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:2rem;">Double glazing &amp; IGU specialists.</h3>
        <p>
          Many Berwick homes from the 1990s and early 2000s have aluminium
          frames that will accept a retrofit IGU &mdash; swapping the
          single pane out for a double-glazed unit while keeping the
          frame in place. The team at
          <a href="https://doubleglazingsoutheast.com.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Double Glazing Southeast</a>
          handle that specialist retrofit work across the Casey corridor.
          They&rsquo;ll assess whether the existing frame can take the
          extra weight (about 2.5x a single pane), check the seals and
          hinges, and quote a glass-only upgrade where it makes sense.
          For frames that can&rsquo;t accept the retrofit, we replace the
          whole window instead. Sharing the assessment between both
          trades means owners get the cheaper option when it&rsquo;s
          viable, instead of being upsold to full replacement
          automatically.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:2rem;">Garage doors &amp; shared safety glazing.</h3>
        <p>
          A garage door isn&rsquo;t a window trade &mdash; but in bushfire
          attack zones (BAL-12.5 or higher across parts of
          Berwick-Beaconsfield, Endeavour Hills foothills) the garage
          door panels, side glazing and any internal access door have to
          share the same BAL compliance as the windows. When owners
          replace both at once we coordinate with
          <a href="https://cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au</a>
          so the BAL certificates align across the whole envelope. They
          also do the side-panel safety glass (Grade A toughened to AS
          2208) that sits beside sectional garage doors &mdash; same
          standard as the windows we install. One supplier, one
          certificate, one paperwork bundle &mdash; cleaner for the owner
          and the building surveyor at sign-off.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:2rem;">House painters &amp; trim repaint.</h3>
        <p>
          Every window replacement damages the surrounding paint line.
          The architrave gets pried, the reveal needs new sealant, the
          flange of the new frame doesn&rsquo;t sit identically to the
          old one. We do basic make-good (sand, prime, sealant) on the
          immediate reveal but for a clean finish across the whole
          architrave and adjoining wall the painter has to come back.
          <a href="https://pakenhamhousepainters.com.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Local painters in Pakenham</a>
          handle the post-install trim repaint on a lot of our jobs
          &mdash; they prep the disturbed sections, blend into the
          existing wall colour, and roll a fresh coat over the touched
          areas. Booking the painter for two days after our install gives
          the sealant time to cure properly before paint goes over it.
          Skip this step and you see the patch line for years.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:2rem;">Plasterer &amp; reveal repair.</h3>
        <p>
          On older Berwick homes with plaster reveals (rather than
          aluminium-clad reveals on modern builds) the plasterer comes in
          between us and the painter. Removing an old timber-framed
          window often takes a chunk of the plaster reveal with it,
          especially if the original install used hard nail-fixings
          straight through the lining. The plasterer patches with
          fibreglass mesh and a base coat, two skim coats over the top,
          then the painter takes over. Adds a day to the project but
          gives a flat finish.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:2rem;">Building surveyor (for non-like-for-like).</h3>
        <p>
          A like-for-like window swap is permit-exempt. Changing the
          opening size, adding a window, converting a sliding door to
          French doors, or installing in a heritage overlay zone all
          require a private building surveyor to issue a permit. We
          engage one on jobs that need it &mdash; same surveyor we use
          for the carport and decking trades, so the paperwork flows
          through one office.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" style="background:#f9fafb;">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Council, standards &amp; references</span>
      <h2>City of Casey references and the standards behind every install.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width:65rem;">
        <p>
          Windows sit at the intersection of energy, safety, bushfire and
          heritage codes. These are the references owners ask about most,
          and the standards we install to on every job regardless of who
          quoted the cheapest.
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-top:1rem;">
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
            <strong>City of Casey</strong> &mdash; building permits,
            heritage overlay maps for Berwick Village, planning permits
            for non-like-for-like changes.
            <a href="https://www.casey.vic.gov.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">casey.vic.gov.au</a>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
            <strong>AS 2047 &mdash; Windows in buildings</strong> &mdash;
            the install standard. Specifies water-penetration resistance,
            air-infiltration limits, structural wind loading and operating
            force tests. Every window we install carries an AS 2047
            compliance label.
            <a href="https://store.standards.org.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Standards Australia</a>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
            <strong>AS 1288 &mdash; Glass in buildings</strong> &mdash; the
            standard for glass thickness, safety-glazing locations, and
            human-impact protection. Anything within 500mm of the floor
            in a habitable room must be Grade A toughened or laminated.
            <a href="https://store.standards.org.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Standards Australia</a>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
            <strong>AS 3959 &mdash; Construction in bushfire-prone areas</strong>
            &mdash; the standard that drives BAL ratings. Parts of Berwick
            (foothill blocks) sit at BAL-12.5 or BAL-19. Windows in those
            zones need specific glazing, screens and frame ratings. Check
            your block&rsquo;s BAL via the CFA map before quoting.
            <a href="https://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/plan-prepare/bushfire-attack-level-bal-ratings" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">CFA &mdash; BAL ratings</a>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
            <strong>NCC Volume 2 &mdash; Energy efficiency</strong> &mdash;
            sets minimum U-values and SHGC (Solar Heat Gain Coefficient)
            for new windows in major renovations. Casey sits in Climate
            Zone 6, where double glazing is the practical baseline.
            <a href="https://ncc.abcb.gov.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">ncc.abcb.gov.au</a>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
            <strong>Victorian Building Authority (VBA)</strong> &mdash;
            registered builder lookup. Any window job over $10K must be
            done by a registered builder. Verify before paying a deposit.
            <a href="https://www.vba.vic.gov.au/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">vba.vic.gov.au</a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">More on what we install</span>
      <h2>Window and sliding door services across Casey.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width:65rem;">
        <p>
          The trade ecosystem is half the picture &mdash; the actual
          glazing, frame and operating-type choice is the other half.
          These pages cover the options we install most often on Casey
          jobs.
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-top:1rem;">
          <li><a href="/services/aluminium-windows/">Aluminium windows</a> &mdash; powder-coated, double-glazed, AS 2047 compliant</li>
          <li><a href="/services/timber-windows/">Timber windows</a> &mdash; cedar, meranti, heritage-style</li>
          <li><a href="/services/sliding-doors/">Sliding doors</a> &mdash; aluminium and timber, double-track and triple-track</li>
          <li><a href="/services/bifold-doors/">Bifold doors</a> &mdash; for indoor-outdoor flow</li>
          <li><a href="/services/awning-windows/">Awning windows</a> &mdash; secondary glazing and ventilation</li>
          <li><a href="/berwick/">Berwick window replacement</a> &mdash; primary service area</li>
          <li><a href="/city-of-casey/">All City of Casey</a> &mdash; Cranbourne, Narre Warren, Endeavour Hills, Hampton Park</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" style="background:var(--ink, #0F2A47);color:#fff;">
    <div class="section-inner" style="text-align:center;">
      <h2 style="color:#fff;">Free quote &mdash; honest Berwick window pricing.</h2>
      <p style="opacity:0.85;max-width:50rem;margin:1rem auto 2rem;">
        Aluminium, timber and double-glazed window replacement across
        Berwick and the City of Casey. AS 2047 install compliance, AS
        1288 safety glazing, BAL-rated options for bushfire zones, City
        of Casey permits coordinated when needed.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a fixed quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
